  "answer": "The following works in the Falsafa corpus use \"gold\" (or its equivalents like *hiraṇya*, *zar*) symbolically or metaphorically, typically to evoke ideas of supreme value, purity, divine origin, spiritual enlightenment, or transcendent beauty surpassing material wealth. Literal references to gold (e.g., as currency, interest rates, or ritual objects in Smṛti texts like *Āṅgirasa Smṛti* or *Bṛhaspati Smṛti*) are excluded, as are purely descriptive uses without deeper symbolism.[^1][^2][^3]\n\n### Cynewulf, *Andreas*\nThe marble pillar addressed by Andreas is deemed \"better than gold\" to emphasize its sacred, inscribed value as a vessel of divine law over mere treasure.[^4]\n\n### Cynewulf, *Elene*\nSouls of the righteous are refined \"like fine gold... cleansed of every impurity\" in the fire of judgment, symbolizing purification and separation from sin.[^5]  \nThe holy Rood (cross) appears \"gleaming with gold,\" symbolizing transcendent glory and divine revelation.[^6]\n\n### Unknown, *Manusmṛti*\nThe primordial seed becomes \"a golden egg,\" symbolizing the radiant, cosmic origin of creation and Brahmā.[^7]\n\n### Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*\nIndia's soil is \"by Truth with gold... crowned,\" metaphorically exalted as a land enriched by divine wisdom and worth.[^8]\n\n### Sheikh Ibrahim Zauq, *Diwan-E-Zauq*\nA lover's \"sallow cheek is worth far more than gold,\" symbolizing the superior purity and alchemy of love.[^9]\n\n### Unknown, *Gaṇapatitattva*\nThe Śiva-Self's path has a color \"like molten gold,\" symbolizing the luminous, joyful route to ultimate spiritual union.[^10]\n\n### Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*\nThe speaker \"boasts of gold he can no longer own,\" metaphorically lamenting illusory past glory or enduring inner worth from old wounds.[^11]\n\nNo other works in the corpus employ gold in a clearly symbolic or metaphorical manner. Poetic mentions of *zar* (gold) in Urdu transliterations (e.g., Iqbal's works) align with the above English translations where symbolic, or are literal/non-symbolic otherwise.",
